# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/active-interest-media] The company was formed in 2003 by private-equity investment firm Wind Point Partners by the acquisition of *Sabot Publishing*, a "special interest" publisher based in Richmond, VA which had been established in 1999 by James Causey and Colonnade Capital.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/active-interest-media] In July 2017, the company announced that it had acquired the United States Team Roping Championships and the TRIAD Classification Agency.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/active-interest-media] In 2020, AIM sold these properties in conjunction with the sale of many of its largest divisions to Pocket Outdoor Media.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/active-interest-media] On 7 November 2012, PixelMags Inc. announced that they had reached an agreement with Active Interest Media to distribute magazine content digitally.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/active-interest-media] In March 2017, Active Interest Media sold its Yachting Promotions Inc. division to Informa for $133 million.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/active-interest-media] The sale included the Fort Lauderdale International Boat Show, Yachts Miami Beach, the Palm Beach International Boat Show, the St.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/active-interest-media] Petersburg Power and Sailboat Show, and the Suncoast Boat Show.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/active-interest-media] On 30 April 2013, Active Interest Media purchased the *SKI* and *Skiing* magazines, Warren Miller Entertainment, and NASTAR from the Bonnier Mountain Group.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/active-interest-media] In 2015, Active Interest Media purchased August Home Publishing, publisher of *Woodsmith* magazine.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/active-interest-media] Chairman and Chief Executive Officer is Efrem Zimbalist III (the son of Efrem Zimbalist, Jr.), formerly of Times Mirror Magazines, a subsidiary of *Times Mirror*.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/active-interest-media] In 2019, Active Interest Media acquired the “collectibles” magazines from F+W Media, which includes *Coins*, *Numismatic News*, *Writer’s Digest*, *Popular Woodworking*, and *Horticulture*.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/active-interest-media] In 2021, Wind Point sold AIM to B&W Communications, a company founded by CEO Andy Clurman.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/active-interest-media] In 2021, Active Interest Media sold its Equine Network properties to Growth Catalyst Partners.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/active-interest-media] On December 3, 2023, Active Interest Media acquired The Taunton Press, publisher of *Fine Woodworking*, ***Fine Homebuilding***, *Green Building Advisor*, *Threads Magazine*, and *Fine Gardening*.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/active-interest-media] In December 2024, the Marine group (sailing, boating, fishing, etc..) was sold to Firecrown Media.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/american-society-of-magazine-editors] The **American Society of Magazine Editors** (**ASME**) is an industry trade group for magazine journalists and editors of magazines published in the United States.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/american-society-of-magazine-editors] ASME includes the editorial leaders of most major consumer magazine in print and digital extensions.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/american-society-of-magazine-editors] The group advocates on behalf of member organizations with respect to First Amendment issues and serves as a networking hub for editors and other industry employees.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/american-society-of-magazine-editors] ASME started as an outgrowth of the editorial committee of the Magazine Publishers of America in 1963.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/american-society-of-magazine-editors] The initial goal of the organization was to defend the First Amendment, protect editorial independence and support the development of journalism.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/american-society-of-magazine-editors] ASME has sponsored the National Magazine Awards (also known as the Ellie Awards) since 1966, along with the Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/american-society-of-magazine-editors] The Ellie Awards honor print and digital magazines that consistently demonstrate superior execution of editorial objectives, innovative techniques, noteworthy journalistic enterprise, and imaginative art direction.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/american-society-of-magazine-editors] In 1966, *Look* received the first award.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/american-society-of-magazine-editors] *Money* received the first award for digital journalism in 1997.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/american-society-of-magazine-editors] Magazine Editors' Hall of Fame and Creative Excellence Awards honor editors, writers, and artists for career-long contributions to magazine journalism.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/american-society-of-magazine-editors] Honorees are chosen by the ASME board of directors.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/american-society-of-magazine-editors] The ASME Best Cover Contest honors the most successful magazine covers of the year.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/american-society-of-magazine-editors] The contest is two-fold: the ASME Best Cover Awards and the ASME Readers' Choice Awards.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/american-society-of-magazine-editors] Each cover entered in the Best Cover Contest is eligible to win both a Best Cover Award and a Readers' Choice Award.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/american-society-of-magazine-editors] ASME hosts the annual American Magazine Media Conference, every year in February, a meeting for magazine media leaders.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/american-society-of-magazine-editors] It is sponsored by the Association of Magazine Media in association with ASME.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/american-society-of-magazine-editors] The conference addresses issues of concern to editors and publishers of print and digital publications.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/american-society-of-magazine-editors] Founded in 1967, the Magazine Internship Program places college juniors in internships at top consumer magazines for 10 weeks every summer.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/american-society-of-magazine-editors] More than 250 alumni of this program now work in magazine media and include the editors in chief of major titles.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/american-society-of-magazine-editors] To be eligible for membership into ASME, one must be employed by a print or digital magazine edited and distributed in the United States, this includes: senior editors, art directors and photography editors.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/american-society-of-magazine-editors] There are also four categories of membership: Chief Editor, Editor, Retired Editor and ASME NEXT.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/american-society-of-magazine-editors] Chief Editors, Editors and Retired Editors are entitled to all the privileges of ASME membership.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/american-society-of-magazine-editors] ASME NEXT members are not eligible to vote in ASME elections.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/american-society-of-magazine-editors] ASME is regulated by a 16-member board of directors, which serve 2-year terms.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/american-society-of-magazine-editors] Directors may be selected for a second 2-year term upon election.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/american-society-of-magazine-editors] Board elections are usually held during the first Wednesday in May at the ASME Annual Meeting.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/american-society-of-magazine-editors] Currently, the chief executive of ASME is Sid Holt.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] The **National Audubon Society** (**Audubon**; /ˈɔːdəbɒn/) is an American non-profit environmental organization dedicated to conservation of birds and their habitats.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] Located in the United States and incorporated in 1905, Audubon is one of the oldest of such organizations in the world.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] There are completely independent Audubon Societies in the United States, which were founded several years earlier such as the Massachusetts Audubon Society, Indiana Audubon Society, and Connecticut Audubon Society.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] The societies are named for 19th century naturalist John James Audubon.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] The society has nearly 500 local chapters, each of which is an independent 501(c)(3) non-profit organization voluntarily affiliated with the National Audubon Society.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] They often organize birdwatching field trips and conservation-related activities.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] It also coordinates the Christmas Bird Count held each December in the U.S., a model of citizen science, in partnership with Cornell Lab of Ornithology, and the Great Backyard Bird Count each February.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] Together with Cornell University, Audubon created eBird, an online database for bird observation.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] The National Audubon Society also has many global partners to help birds that migrate beyond the U.S.'s borders, including BirdLife International based in Great Britain, Bird Studies Canada, American Bird Conservancy, and many partners in Latin America and in the Caribbean.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] Audubon's International Alliances Program (IAP) brings together people throughout the Western Hemisphere to work together to implement conservation solutions at Important Birds Areas (IBAs).
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] In 1886, *Forest and Stream* editor George Bird Grinnell was appalled by the negligent mass slaughter of birds that he saw taking place.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] As a boy, Grinnell had avidly read *Ornithological Biography*, a work by the bird painter John James Audubon; he also lived in his early years in a development of the former Audubon estate, Audubon Park in upper Manhattan, and attended a school for boys conducted by Lucy Audubon.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] The Audubon name would become the namesake of the society he founded, and after its failure, that of local, state, and a national organization bearing that name.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] In 1890, a Chicago-based Audubon Society was started under the presidency of E.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] About 70 persons joined and the Society was incorporated in 1893.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] Within a year of Grinnell founding it his early Audubon Society claimed 39,000 members, eventually growing to 48,862.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] Each member signed a pledge to "not molest birds".
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] Prominent members included jurist Oliver Wendell Holmes Jr., abolitionist minister Henry Ward Beecher, and poet John Greenleaf Whittier.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] In under a decade this society was discontinued, but the name and plan survived.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] Organizations for the protection of birds were not a wholly new idea.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] Even before Grinnell's Audubon Society was organized, the American Ornithologists' Union, founded in 1883, was aware of the dangers facing many birds in the United States.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] There were, however, influential ornithologists who defended the collection of birds.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] Cory, the president-elect of the AOU refused to attend a meeting of the District of Columbia Audubon Society stating that "I do not protect birds.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] In 1895, a second iteration of the Audubon Society was created, with an unbroken history that traces to today.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] Cousins and Boston socialites, Harriet Hemenway and Minna B.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] Hall, disturbed by the destruction left by plume hunters, organized a series of afternoon teas with other wealthy local women, encouraging them to avoid feathered garments.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] They also sent literature asking these women to, in Hall's words, "join a society for the protection of birds, especially the egret".
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] Later that same year, they founded the Massachusetts Audubon Society.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] Over 900 women came together with Hemenway and Hall, and across the country, many others were doing the same.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] These boycotts were largely successful, and the efforts of the early society members helped bring about the end of the plume trade and assisted in the introduction of early conservation legislation such as the Migratory Bird Treaty Act.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] In 1896, Pennsylvania created their Audubon Society, and during the next few years, bird lovers in many other states followed suit.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] Louis Audubon Society (SLAS) was established in 1916 as the St Louis Bird Club.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] In 1944, the Bird Club became the first local Audubon chapter in the United States.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] The national committee of Audubon societies was organized at a meeting held in Washington, D.C. in 1902.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] 1905 saw the organization of the National Association of Audubon Societies for the Protection of Wild Birds and Animals; William Dutcher was president, and T.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] Gilbert Pearson was secretary and financial agent.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] During this time, Albert Willcox provided financial support, more than $331,072 in 1905 and 1906.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] At the end of 1906, the Association had an interest-bearing endowment fund of more than $336,000 and an income from other sources of approximately $9,000.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] Birds in the United States were threatened by market hunting as well as for the fashion industry.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] Pressure from shooting enthusiasts was intense.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] For example, great auks, whose habit of crowding together on rocks and beaches made them especially easy to hunt, had been driven to extinction early in the century.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] During one week in the spring of 1897, nature author Florence Merriam claimed to have seen 2,600 robins for sale in one market stall in Washington alone.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] By the start of the 20th century, the sale of bird flesh had never been greater.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] The second equally great threat to the bird population was the desire for their plumage.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] In the late 1890s, the American Ornithologists' Union estimated that five million birds were killed annually for the fashion market.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] In the final quarter of the 19th century, plumes, and even whole birds, decorated the hair, hats, and dresses of women.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] Poachers killed game warden Guy Bradley on July 8, 1905; poachers killed Game Warden Columbus G.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] McLeod in November 1908 in Florida and Audubon Society employee Pressly Reeves of South Carolina also in 1908.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] Public opinion soon turned on the fashion industry.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] By 1920, similar laws were enacted in about 12 other states.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] Audubon Society activities are responsible for many laws for the establishment of game commissions and game warden forces or prohibiting the sale of game.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] In 1918, the NAS actively lobbied for the Federal Migratory Bird Treaty Act.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] In the 1920s, the organization also played a vital role in convincing the U.S. government to protect vital wildlife areas by including them in a National Wildlife Refuge system.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] The association also acquired land through purchases and donation.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] The **Theodore Roosevelt Sanctuary and Audubon Center** in Oyster Bay, New York was donated to New York Audubon in 1923 by Emlen Roosevelt and Christine Roosevelt in memory of their cousin, who is buried in the adjacent Youngs Memorial Cemetery.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] The **Audubon Center** of Greenwich, Connecticut was founded in 1943.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] Rainey Wildlife Sanctuary in Louisiana was acquired in 1924, and at 26,000 acres (110 km2) it is still the largest.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] In the late 20th century, the organization began to place a new emphasis on the development of Centers in urban locations, including Brooklyn, New York; East Los Angeles, California; Phoenix, Arizona; and Seattle, Washington.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] In 1934, with membership at a low of 3,500, and with the nation in the Great Depression, John H.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] He was a World War I aviator and ardent bird lover, and also a businessman, and he set about to invigorate the society and bolster its budget prosperity through publication.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] Baker began publishing book-length field guides on major forms of bird and mammal life.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] Soon, in association with New York publisher Alfred A.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] Knopf, the *Audubon Field Guide*s became a staple of every artist's and environmentalist's library.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] Today, many Audubon field guides have been adapted for mobile phone apps.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] This field guide series covers a wide range of nature-related topics, including the night sky, rocks and minerals, wildflowers, and many animals.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] This series has sold 18 million copies and uses photographs instead of the commissioned paintings or other drawings that many other field guides possess, such as the Peterson Field Guides.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] During the post–World War II period, the NAS was consumed by the battle over the pesticide DDT.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] As early as 1960, the society circulated draft legislation to establish pesticide control agencies at the state level.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] In 1962 the publication of the book *Silent Spring* by long-time Audubon member Rachel Carson gave the campaign against "persistent pesticides" a huge national forum.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] Following her death in 1964, the NAS established a fund devoted strictly to the various legal fights in the war against DDT.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] Today, Audubon selects outstanding women in conservation to receive its prestigious Rachel Carson Award.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] Honorees include Bette Midler, singer, actress, and founder of the New York Restoration Project; Dr.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] Sylvia Earle, oceanographer and founder of Deep Search International; Majora Carter, founder and executive director of Sustainable South Bronx; actress and conservation activist Sigourney Weaver; and Natural Resources Defense Council president Frances Beinecke.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] Through the 1960s and 1970s, the society began to use its influence to focus attention on a wider range of environmental issues and became involved in developing major new environmental protection policies and laws.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] Audubon staff and members helped legislators pass the Clean Air, Clean Water, Wild and Scenic Rivers, and Endangered Species acts.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] In 1969, the society opened an office in Washington, D.C., in an effort to keep legislators informed of Audubon's priorities.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] By the 1970s, NAS had also extended to global interests.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] One area that NAS became actively involved with was whaling.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] Between 1973 and 1974 alone, the poorly regulated whaling industry had succeeded in harvesting 30,000 whales.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] But by 1985, following the 37th annual meeting of the International Whaling Commission in Bournemouth, England, which was attended by officials from the National Audubon Society and other U.S.-based environmental organizations, a worldwide moratorium on whaling was declared.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] So successful has this moratorium been in restoring populations of many whales, that "non-consumptive uses of whales" may once again be permitted in some areas.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] During the 1980s and 1990s, the National Audubon Society produced a notable series of nature documentary television specials, many of which were entitled *The World of Audubon*.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] These included specials on many animals other than birds (the traditional focus of this organization) and on natural areas such as the Great Lakes.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] This series included a special documenting the rescue efforts to save the black-footed ferret from extinction.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] Arthur Unger of *The Christian Science Monitor* reviewed this special very favorably and wrote that this special was "further proof that the Audubon series deserves a place in television's splendid wildlife triumvirate alongside *Nature* and *National Geographic Specials*".
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] The Audubon Medal is given in recognition of outstanding achievement in the field of conservation and environmental protection.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] 52 people have received the honor in Audubon's 108-year history.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] In 2011, Audubon created a new model for positioning energy transmission lines along the East Coast to help preserve bird and wildlife habitat.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] Audubon President David Yarnold has made environmentally friendly siting for renewable energy one of the organization's highest priorities.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] Audubon played an important part in bird rescue and Gulf Coast wetlands recovery efforts in the aftermath of the April 20, 2010, BP oil spill in the Gulf of Mexico, the largest accidental marine oil spill in the history of the petroleum industry.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] Audubon recruited over 34,000 volunteers to assist in rescuing, cleaning and releasing injured brown pelicans and other water birds.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] In addition, Audubon was a leader in pushing for legislation to use BP oil spill penalties to rebuild the Gulf Coast.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] Audubon's Mississippi River and Louisiana Coastal Initiatives have been helping to restore coastal wetlands and to rebuild Mississippi River delta marshlands.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] The Mississippi Delta loses an area the size of Manhattan to the sea every year, stripping away coastal protections for both human communities and wildlife habitat.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] Audubon's Important Bird Area program has been protecting 370 million acres along migratory bird flyways in the United States and is a key part of Audubon's work with BirdLife International and other conservationists around the globe.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] Audubon is leading the campaign for U.S.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] Congressional Reauthorization of the Neotropical Migratory Bird Conservation Act which would generate as much as $100 million each year to advance hemispheric bird conservation.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] In Wyoming and across the Intermountain west, Audubon's Sagebrush Initiative works with industry, government, ranchers and conservationists to protect 15 million acres of greater sage grouse Core habitat.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] It also helps promote the development of renewable energy projects in the area.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] Audubon also helped to secure the preservation of 240,000 acres of wild lands at the Tejon Ranch, the largest land conservation area created in California history.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] In March 2020, the Arkansas chapter of the Audubon Society announced its plan to spend $80,000 to install solar panels on its grounds, which will make their Little Rock office the state's first nonprofit to utilize 100% solar energy.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] Nature centers and wildlife sanctuaries continue to be an important part of Audubon's work to educate and inspire the public about the environment and how to conserve it.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] Some of the Audubon's earliest nature centers are still teaching young and old alike about the natural world.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] In 2016, Audubon's Hog Island Camp in Maine marked its 80th anniversary.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] Audubon's national network currently includes nearly 500 local chapters, 23 state programs, 41 nature centers.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] After nearly three-quarters of a century, the National Wildlife Refuge Campaign also remains a key component of overall NAS policy.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] An online database is provided by Audubon that displays which native plants are important for birds in different areas that is searchable by USA zip code.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] Audubon has recently expanded its outreach about the detrimental impact of invasive species like Norway maples, Tatarian honeysuckle and other ecological threats to human health and wildlife.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] The Audubon society opposes drilling for gas on national reserves.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] Natural gas has been drilled for and produced at its Paul J.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] The society said it was legally compelled to allow gas and oil drilling at the sanctuary under the terms of the land's donation by its original owners.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] This explanation, however, has been challenged.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] The presence of oil and gas drilling on Audubon's sanctuaries has been used to illustrate the difference between private and public decision-making.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] An August 26, 2009, an open letter was sent to the U.S.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] Senate Environment and Public Works Committee calling for stronger climate protections, including an end to subsidies for drilling companies.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] Lufkin Prize for Environmental Leadership is a new award that recognizes Dan W.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] Lufkin's lifetime commitment to the environment and honors individuals who have dedicated their lives to on-the-ground conservation.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] As part of this award, the recipient receives a $100,000 cash prize, made through an endowment established by Dan's family and friends, to help further his or her conservation efforts.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] This award will become a signature prize in the field of conservation innovation.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] George Archibald was the inaugural Dan W.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] Lufkin Prize recipient for his tireless efforts to protect all species of cranes and their habitats throughout the world.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] Lufkin as the Donor of the Day, for the creation of this new Audubon prize.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] The Rachel Carson Award is part of a broader Audubon initiative called Women in Conservation Project.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] There is also the Women in Conservation Fellowship.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] These internships are given to women who wish to learn about areas such as public relations, management, and event planning.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] In September 2014, the Audubon Society released its *Audubon Birds and Climate Change* report which found that expected changes to North American climate will have a major, detrimental impact on birds in the United States.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] The scope of the report includes 588 species of birds and found that 314 of those species could lose up to half of their climatic range during the 21st century.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] The society was named in honor of John James Audubon, a Franco-American ornithologist and naturalist who painted, cataloged, and described the birds of North America in his famous *Birds of America* book (1827–1838).
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] Despite these accolades, John James Audubon's legacy has been tarnished by numerous accusations of plagiarism and scientific fraud, which his biographers (and Audubon's leadership) have routinely dismissed or minimized, even while admitting to his history of racism and slavery.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] John James Audubon collected human skulls to assist the scientific racism work of Samuel G.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] In the wake of the protests following the murder of George Floyd, there have been public appeals to strip the name Audubon from the society and change the names of species that honor him.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] The Audubon Society has publicly supported the removal of Confederate monuments, including acknowledging that "it's not just an issue of physical monuments".
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] An internal Board of Directors vote in 2023 resulted in a decision to retain the Audubon name for the national organization, with the subsequent resignation of three of its 26 board members.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] In February 2023, the union representing Audubon employees renamed itself The Bird Union.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] Seven months earlier, in July 2022, the Seattle chapter of Audubon announced it would change the name, and later announced the new name would be Birds Connect Seattle, effective June 2023.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] Shortly after the Seattle chapter's announcement in February, the Chicago chapter also announced it would change its name.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] In March 2023, the New York City chapter announced that after studying the issue for eight months, it would change its name; Jessica Wilson, executive director of the NYC chapter, stated that the current name "served as a barrier to getting all New Yorkers involved".
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] Chapters in other cities such as Washington, D.C., Portland, Oregon, and Buffalo, New York, have made similar announcements.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] Following layoffs and complaints about diversity and inclusion programs, an Audubon union organizing drive went public in March 2021 with about 400 workers.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] Yarnold stepped down the next month following an internal audit into Audubon's workplace culture and toxic workplace complaints.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] Elizabeth Gray was named Audubon's CEO in November, 2021.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/audubon] The National Audubon Society publishes a bi-monthly magazine called *Audubon*.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/betsy-talbot-blackwell] Blackwell was born in New York City to Hayden Talbot, a playwright and author, and Benedict B.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/betsy-talbot-blackwell] Elizabeth's Academy, a Catholic girls' school, though she was not a Catholic.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/betsy-talbot-blackwell] Blackwell began her career as an assistant fashion editor at *Charm* magazine from 1923 to 1928, afterwards becoming a fashion editor at *Mademoiselle* under the assumed name of Elizabeth Rich.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/betsy-talbot-blackwell] From 1937 until her retirement in 1971, she served as the editor-in-chief of the magazine.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/betsy-talbot-blackwell] During her tenure at *Mademoiselle*, Blackwell oversaw increased circulation—from 178,000 in 1939 to 540,000 in 1953 to nearly a million in 1971—a change in focus towards young career women and the introduction of a literary aspect to the magazine.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/betsy-talbot-blackwell] Many well-known authors were published in *Mademoiselle* during her time as editor-in-chief, including Eudora Welty, Truman Capote, William Faulkner, and Joyce Carol Oates.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/betsy-talbot-blackwell] During her editorship, the magazine started the practice of allowing college women to write and publish an issue each summer.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/betsy-talbot-blackwell] The summer guest editorship program included Sylvia Plath, Joan Didion, Mona Simpson, Ann Beattie, Francine du Plessix Gray, Meg Wolitzer, Betsey Johnson, Ali MacGraw, and Diane Johnson.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/betsy-talbot-blackwell] She died in 1985 while being treated for emphysema.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/betsy-talbot-blackwell] She was survived by her son and stepdaughter through her marriage to James Madison Blackwell.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/betsy-talbot-blackwell] Papers relating to her life, including her personal and professional correspondence, along with her work at *Mademoiselle*, were bequeathed by her husband to the American Heritage Center, operated by the University of Wyoming.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/betsy-talbot-blackwell] In 1942, she received the Neiman Marcus Fashion Award for her contributions to fashion, and in 1949 became the first woman to be elected to the board of New York publisher Street & Smith.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/business-network] A **business network** is a complex, enduring, and interdependent web of business relationships among market and non-market actors that allow firms to co-create value in their business environment.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/business-network] Firms influence their markets by managing and signalling their network positions, facilitating entry of new actors, or removing other actors, for instance, through disintermediation, which means eliminating the middleman.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/business-network] When some actors within a business network have joint strategic intents and work together to achieve certain objectives, then the network is called a strategic business net.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/business-network] These objectives, which are strategic and operational, are adopted by business networks based on their role in the market.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/business-network] In the late 20th century, the study of business networks emerged in the field of industrial markets.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/business-network] Researchers analyzed the transactions and communications beneath the visible flows of products, inquiries, sales visits and negotiations, and beyond the visible growth and prosperity of some companies and the failure of others.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/business-network] Snehota and Hakansson (1995) explain: For more than twenty years, we have analyzed business networks for answers to the many questions about industrial markets.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/business-network] Unlike consumer markets, industrial markets are not generally known to the public, nor to many management scholars.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/business-network] We have been surprised by the complexity of industrial markets and at the same time by the apparent smoothness of their working.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/business-network] Gradually, we have acquired respect for their importance and complexity and learned how they work.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/business-network] Another study on business networks was carried out by Ecorys between 2013 and 2014.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/business-network] This study was specific to EU-level business networks and was financed by the European Commission.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/business-network] The main objective of the study was to investigate and highlight the new forms of inter-firm collaboration and to propose possible measures to support and coordinate them in Europe where and if appropriate.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/business-network] This study included the objectives and categorization of business networks.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/business-network] Business networks have two types of objectives — strategic and operational — that are adopted depending on the role of the business network in the market.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/business-network] Business networks can be divided into two main categories: business associations and company aggregations.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/business-network] Business associations — also called business networks as business associations — provide member companies with a platform and conditions for cooperation to meet an objective.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/business-network] The companies decide if they want to cooperate to achieve that objective.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/business-network] Business associations create a level playing field for cooperation among companies.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/business-network] They have a stable and well-functioning governance structure.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/business-network] The members may pay a fee to the association.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/business-network] In return, the business association monitors and meets the needs of their members and proactively develops and provides new services.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/business-network] This is the key task of business associations.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/business-network] Business associations provide services that are generally more professional, extensive, and cost effective compared to services offered by individual members.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/business-network] In a business association, there is a direct link between the business association (central body) and each of its constituent members.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/business-network] This is displayed with solid bidirectional arrows (refer to Figure 1).
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/business-network] The members may or may not choose to cooperate with each other, displayed with dashed lines between companies.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/business-network] Business associations are further categorized by sector or by location and scope.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/business-network] Company aggregations — also called business networks as company aggregations — are formed by companies, which decide to cooperate and aggregate.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/business-network] Unlike business associations, these companies have already taken the decision to work together on a joint set of objectives.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/business-network] In a company aggregation, companies collaborate directly with each other without a representative and/or a servicing association.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/business-network] The aggregation of the companies can be formalized through a business contract.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/business-network] Company aggregations have two forms of cooperation: horizontal and vertical.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/business-network] Business network companies — that is, platform and network-based companies — outperform traditional companies.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/business-network] Some companies that follow a business network model include Trepup, eBay, Red Hat, Visa, Uber, TripAdvisor, Alibaba.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/business-network] Clusters are a network of connected businesses, suppliers, and associates in a specific field that are all located in the same geographical area.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/business-network] Conversely, companies in a business network are not bound by geographical locations or sectors, and can be focused around any specific objective.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/business-network] A joint venture is a new legal entity created by two or more companies, generally characterized by shared ownership, shared returns and risks, and shared governance.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/business-network] The companies come together to accomplish a specific task, such as a project or a business activity.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/business-network] In a business network, on the other hand, the autonomy of each of the companies is preserved and no new legal entity is formed.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/business-network] The companies capitalize on the network to create opportunities and expand their individual business interests.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/business-wire] Business Wire was founded in 1961 by Lorry I.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/business-wire] It started by sending releases to 16 media outlets in California.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/business-wire] Business Wire launched its website in May 1995.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/business-wire] In 2000, ahead of its main competitor PR Newswire, Business Wire ended the practice of distributing news to financial outlets 15 minutes before anyone else, to provide immediate, equal access to company information as noted by the SEC's fair disclosure regulation (Reg FD).
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/business-wire] Business Wire's first wholly owned European operation launched in 2001, with the opening of an office in London.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/business-wire] On June 1, 2005, Business Wire entered the German Ad-Hoc market with a disclosure network for companies with primary or secondary listings on the Deutsche Boerse.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/business-wire] The service was established in compliance with BaFin, Germany's national securities regulator.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/business-wire] On September 15, 2005, Business Wire established Regulatory Disclosure networks in France, Sweden, Switzerland and Luxembourg.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/business-wire] The move came in anticipation of the anticipated implementation of the EU's Transparency Obligations Directive (TOD).
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/business-wire] On January 1, 2007, Autorité des marchés financiers, the French Financial Markets Regulator, approved Business Wire to operate as a Regulatory Disclosure Service in France.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/business-wire] On January 10, 2005, Business Wire established an Asian hub with the opening of its Tokyo, Japan bureau, and later that year added Japanese, making the site available in seven languages.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/business-wire] On January 17, 2006, Berkshire Hathaway announced that it was purchasing Business Wire for an undisclosed amount.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/business-wire] This acquisition was completed on March 1, 2006.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/business-wire] In 2008, Business Wire partnered with ImpreMedia to launch LatinoWire, a news distribution service that distributes brand content to Hispanic websites, media outlets, journalists and bloggers.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/business-wire] In 2011, Business Wire received a patent for the technological process of optimizing and distributing press releases to maximize their ability to be found and tracked in leading search engines.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/business-wire] The originality of the patent was questioned by SEO expert Danny Sullivan.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/business-wire] On September 23, 2013, Business Wire announces exclusive distribution partnership with *VentureBeat* On November 3, 2013, Business Wire opened its office in Hong Kong.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/business-wire] In January 2014, Business Wire launched a new news and content distribution enhancement service.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/business-wire] In April 2017, its chief executive officer and president, Cathy Baron Tamraz, retired and was replaced by longtime CFO Geff Scott.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/columbia-university-graduate-school-of-journalism] The **Columbia University Graduate School of Journalism** is the journalism school of Columbia University, located in the Morningside Heights neighborhood of Manhattan, New York City, New York, United States.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/columbia-university-graduate-school-of-journalism] Admissions to the school are highly selective; traditionally drawing upon an international student body.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/columbia-university-graduate-school-of-journalism] Alumni have gone on to win Pulitzer Prizes, or have become newsroom leaders in respected publications.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/columbia-university-graduate-school-of-journalism] It also co-sponsors the National Magazine Awards with the American Society of Magazine Editors, which administers the program.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/columbia-university-graduate-school-of-journalism] The school has an accreditation from the Association for Education in Journalism and Mass Communication.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/columbia-university-graduate-school-of-journalism] In 1892, Joseph Pulitzer, a Hungarian-born newspaper magnate, offered Columbia University president Seth Low funding to establish the world's first school of journalism.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/columbia-university-graduate-school-of-journalism] He sought to elevate a profession viewed more often as a common trade learned through an apprenticeship.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/columbia-university-graduate-school-of-journalism] His idea was for a center of enlightened journalism in pursuit of knowledge as well as skills in the service of democracy.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/columbia-university-graduate-school-of-journalism] "It will impart knowledge—not for its own sake, but to be used for the public service," Pulitzer wrote in a now landmark, lead essay of the May 1904 issue of the *North American Review*.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/columbia-university-graduate-school-of-journalism] The university was resistant to the idea.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/columbia-university-graduate-school-of-journalism] But Low's successor, Nicholas Murray Butler, was more receptive to the plan.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/columbia-university-graduate-school-of-journalism] Pulitzer was set on creating his vision at Columbia and offered it a $2 million gift, one-quarter of which was to be used to establish prizes in journalism and the arts.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/columbia-university-graduate-school-of-journalism] It took years of negotiations and Pulitzer's death in October 1911 to finalize plans.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/columbia-university-graduate-school-of-journalism] On September 30, 1912, classes began with 79 undergraduate and postgraduate students, including a dozen women.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/columbia-university-graduate-school-of-journalism] Veteran journalist Talcott Williams was installed as the school's director.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/columbia-university-graduate-school-of-journalism] When not attending classes and lectures, students scoured the city for news.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/columbia-university-graduate-school-of-journalism] Their more advanced classmates were assigned to cover a visit by U.S.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/columbia-university-graduate-school-of-journalism] President William Howard Taft, a sensational police murder trial and a women's suffrage march.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/columbia-university-graduate-school-of-journalism] A student from China went undercover to report on a downtown cocaine den.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/columbia-university-graduate-school-of-journalism] A journalism building was constructed the following year at 2950 Broadway and 116th Street on the western end of the campus.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/columbia-university-graduate-school-of-journalism] A statue of Thomas Jefferson was installed in June 1914 as a symbol of "free inquiry" exemplified by the debates between him and fellow American founder and Columbia alumnus, Alexander Hamilton, a statute of whom was unveiled directly across campus in front of Hamilton Hall six years earlier.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/columbia-university-graduate-school-of-journalism] In 1935, Dean Carl Ackerman, a 1913 alumnus, led the school's transition to become the first graduate school of journalism in the United States.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/columbia-university-graduate-school-of-journalism] As the school's reach and reputation spread (due in part to an adjunct faculty of working New York journalists and a tenured full-time faculty that included Pulitzer winners Douglas Southall Freeman and Henry F.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/columbia-university-graduate-school-of-journalism] Pringle and *Life Begins at Forty* author Walter B.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/columbia-university-graduate-school-of-journalism] Pitkin), it began offering coursework in television news and documentary filmmaking in addition to its focus on newspapers and radio.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/columbia-university-graduate-school-of-journalism] The Maria Moors Cabot Prizes, the oldest international awards in journalism, were founded in 1938, honoring reporting in Latin America and the Caribbean.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/columbia-university-graduate-school-of-journalism] The Alfred I. duPont-Columbia Awards for excellence in broadcast journalism moved to the school in 1968.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/columbia-university-graduate-school-of-journalism] In 1958, the Columbia Journalism Award, the school's highest honor, was established to recognize a person of overarching accomplishment and distinguished service to journalism.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/columbia-university-graduate-school-of-journalism] Three years later, the school began publishing the *Columbia Journalism Review*.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/columbia-university-graduate-school-of-journalism] After joining the tenured faculty in 1950, veteran United Nations correspondent John Hohenberg became the inaugural administrator of the Pulitzer Prizes in 1954, a secondary appointment that he would hold until 1976.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/columbia-university-graduate-school-of-journalism] Ackerman was succeeded as dean in 1954 by former Assistant Secretary of State for Public Affairs Edward W.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/columbia-university-graduate-school-of-journalism] In 1966, the school began awarding the National Magazine Awards in association with the American Society of Magazine Editors.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/columbia-university-graduate-school-of-journalism] Friendly was appointed the same year to the tenured faculty and enhanced the broadcast journalism program alongside former NBC News correspondent Elie Abel, who served as dean from 1970 to 1979.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/columbia-university-graduate-school-of-journalism] Abel was succeeded by former *Newsweek* editor and prominent New York socialite Osborn Elliott (1979–1986), who in turn was succeeded by longtime Bill Moyers collaborator Joan Konner (1988–1996), the school's only female dean to date.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/columbia-university-graduate-school-of-journalism] By the 1970s, the Reporting and Writing 1 (RW1) course had become the cornerstone of the school's basic curriculum.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/columbia-university-graduate-school-of-journalism] The Knight‐Bagehot Fellowship was created in 1975 to enrich economics and business journalism.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/columbia-university-graduate-school-of-journalism] In 1985, the Delacorte Center for Magazine Journalism was founded.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/columbia-university-graduate-school-of-journalism] While serving as Pulitzer administrator, former *The New York Times* managing editor Seymour Topping joined the tenured faculty in 1994.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/columbia-university-graduate-school-of-journalism] A doctoral program was established in 1998 by communications theorist James W.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/columbia-university-graduate-school-of-journalism] As a result of industry changes forced by digital media, the school in 2013 erased distinctions between types of media, such as newspaper, broadcast, magazine and new media, as specializations in its master of science curriculum.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/columbia-university-graduate-school-of-journalism] The Toni Stabile Center for Investigative Journalism, dedicated to training select students interested in pursuing careers in investigative journalism, opened in 2006.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/columbia-university-graduate-school-of-journalism] A year later, the Spencer Fellowship was created to focus on long-form reporting.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/columbia-university-graduate-school-of-journalism] The Dart Center for Journalism and Trauma relocated to Columbia in 2009 to focus on media coverage of trauma, conflict and tragedy.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/columbia-university-graduate-school-of-journalism] In 2010, the Tow Center for Digital Journalism was created.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/columbia-university-graduate-school-of-journalism] The Brown Institute for Media Innovation was launched under the aegis of former Bell Labs statistician and data scientist Mark Henry Hansen in 2012.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/columbia-university-graduate-school-of-journalism] The school's ten-month Master of Science (M.S.) program offers aspiring and experienced journalists the opportunity to study the skills, art and ethics of journalism by reporting and writing stories that range from short news pieces to complex narrative features.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/columbia-university-graduate-school-of-journalism] Some students interested in investigative reporting are selected to study at the Stabile Center for Investigative Journalism, a specialization of the M.S. program.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/columbia-university-graduate-school-of-journalism] Documentary and data journalism specialization programs are offered as well.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/columbia-university-graduate-school-of-journalism] The M.S. program is also offered on a part-time basis.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/columbia-university-graduate-school-of-journalism] A year-long M.S. program in data journalism teaches the skills for finding, collecting and analyzing data for storytelling, presentation and investigative reporting.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/columbia-university-graduate-school-of-journalism] The school offers several dual-degree programs in collaboration with other schools at Columbia: journalism and computer science, journalism and international affairs, journalism and law, journalism and business, and journalism and religion.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/columbia-university-graduate-school-of-journalism] The school also offers international dual-degree programs with Sciences Po in Paris, France and the University of Witwatersrand in Johannesburg, South Africa.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/columbia-university-graduate-school-of-journalism] The smaller and more specialized, nine-month Master of Arts (M.A.) program is for experienced journalists interested in focusing on a particular subject area: politics, science, business and economics or arts and culture.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/columbia-university-graduate-school-of-journalism] M.A. students work closely with journalism professors and take courses in other academic departments and schools at the university.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/columbia-university-graduate-school-of-journalism] The doctoral program draws upon the resources of Columbia in a multidisciplinary approach to the study of communications.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/columbia-university-graduate-school-of-journalism] Ph.D. students craft individual courses of study to acquire deep knowledge in an area of concentration through research and coursework in disciplines ranging from history, sociology or religion to business or international affairs.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/columbia-university-graduate-school-of-journalism] A six-week graduate-level course on book, magazine, and digital publishing, known as the Columbia Publishing Course, has been offered since 2000, when the program transferred from Radcliffe College.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/cynthia-leive] Leive's career began at The Paris Review, where she was an intern while still a student at Swarthmore College.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/cynthia-leive] After graduating, Leive took an editorial assistant position at *Glamour* and worked alongside Ruth Whitney, who was at the helm of the magazine for 31 years.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/cynthia-leive] After 11 years, Leive left *Glamour* as deputy editor and joined *Self* magazine as editor-in-chief.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/cynthia-leive] During Leive's tenure, *Self’s* circulation increased by eleven percent.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/cynthia-leive] Leive rejoined *Glamour* magazine as editor-in-chief in 2001.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/cynthia-leive] She was behind creation and success of glamour.com which together with the magazine reach one out of every eight American women, with 9.7 million print readers and 11 million unique users online.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/cynthia-leive] Leive also founded The Girl Project to support girls’ education, making *Glamour* the first women's media brand with a nonprofit initiative.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/cynthia-leive] She serves on the board of directors for The International Women’s Media Foundation and is a former president of the American Society of Magazine Editors.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/cynthia-leive] Leive is a board member of Swarthmore College (her alma mater), as well as the Brooklyn Public Library.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/cynthia-leive] In 2022, Leive served as a judge for that year's American Mosaic Journalism Prize.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/cynthia-leive] In 2002, *Crain’s* put Leive on its "Top 40 Under 40" list, and Leive was also named one of *Gotham* magazine's most powerful "Women Under 40 in New York City".
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/cynthia-leive] After 16 years at the helm of *Glamour,* Leive announced she would be leaving by the end 2017.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/cynthia-leive] For her outstanding service to the magazine, publishing industry, and women around the world, she received *Glamour's* biggest honor - a Woman of the Year Award.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/cynthia-leive] Among women who celebrated Leive's accomplishments were former first ladies Hillary Clinton and Michelle Obama, former long-time president of Planned Parenthood Cecile Richards, and *Vogue*'s editor-in-chief Anna Wintour.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/cynthia-leive] Leive was born to a Jewish family in McLean, Virginia.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/cynthia-leive] A 1988 graduate of Swarthmore College, Leive was an English literature major and minored in religion.
[src:american-society-of-magazine-editors/cynthia-leive] Leive lives in New York City with her husband, film producer Howard Bernstein, her daughter, Lucy, and her son, Isaac.
